###########################################################################
#  eq_braces_brackets - @Eq exercising the three fence shapes (parens,    #
#  square brackets, curly braces) together in one display, each driven   #
#  by the `left ... right ...` grow operator so the fences scale with    #
#  the body they wrap.  Companion to eq_braced_systems.lt (which pins    #
#  the piecewise-system case) and eq_matrix.lt (single-shape brackets);  #
#  this fills the multi-shape, single-line gap.                          #
###########################################################################

@SysInclude { eq }
@SysInclude { doc }
@Doc @Text @Begin
@PP
A single expression nesting all three of Lout's fence shapes, each
grown by @Code "left .. right .." to wrap its body:
@DP
@CentredDisplay @Eq {
   f ( x ) = left "{"
      a left [
         b left ( x sup 2 + 1 right )
         + c left ( x - 1 right )
      right ]
      + d
   right "}"
}
@DP
With nested fractions inside the brackets to force vertical growth:
@DP
@CentredDisplay @Eq {
   y = left [
      { 1 } over { 1 + { x sup 2 } over { 1 - x } }
   right ]
   + left "{" { a + b } over { c + d } right "}"
}
@End @Text
